(469, 1, '2009-01-04 19:50:11', '2009-01-04 19:50:11', '[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nT.D Huang, S. Sorgenfrei, P. Gong, R. Levicky, K.L. Shepard, "<a href="/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/david_jssc_2009.pdf" target="_blank">A 0.18-um CMOS Array Sensor for Integrated Time-Resolved Fluorescence Detection</a>," IEEE Journal of Solid-State Circuits, 44, 5, (May 2009), pp. 1644-1654.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nThis paper describes the design of an active, integrated CMOS sensor array for fluorescence applications which enables time-gated, time-resolved fluorescence spectroscopy. The 64-by-64 array is sensitive to photon densities as low as 8x8 x 10<sup>6</sup> photons/cm with 64-point averaging and, through a differential pixel design, has a measured impulse response of better than 800 ps. Applications include both active microarrays and high-frame-rate imagers for fluorescence lifetime imaging microscopy.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]', 'A 0.18-um CMOS Array Sensor for Integrated Time-Resolved Fluorescence Detection', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'a-0-18-um-cmos-array-sensor-for-integrated-time-resolved-fluorescence-detection', '', '', '2017-04-04 20:02:46', '2017-04-04 20:02:46', '', 0, 'http://bioee.dev/?p=469', 0, 'post', '', 0),
