(516, 1, '2011-01-04 21:45:05', '2011-01-04 21:45:05', '[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nRosenstein, J.; Ray, V.; Drndic, M.; Shepard, K.L.; "<a href="/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/rosenstein_transducers2011.pdf" target="_blank">Nanopore DNA sensors in CMOS with on-chip low-noise preamplifiers</a>," Solid-State Sensors, Actuators, and Microsystems Conference (Transducers), 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nTechnological advances in fluorescent probes, solid-state imagers, and microscopy techniques have enabled biomolecular studies at the single-molecule level. Fluorescent techniques are highly specific but their bandwidth is fundamentally limited by the number of photons that can be collected. New electronic sensors including nanopores and nanotube field-effect transistors offer different tradeoffs between bandwidth and noise levels. Here, we discuss the performance of these direct solid-state interfaces and their potential for sensing single-molecule dynamics at shorter timescales.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]', 'Nanopore DNA sensors in CMOS with on-chip low-noise preamplifiers', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'nanopore-dna-sensors-in-cmos-with-on-chip-low-noise-preamplifiers', '', '', '2017-04-04 21:58:47', '2017-04-04 21:58:47', '', 0, 'http://bioee.dev/?p=516', 0, 'post', '', 0),
