(557, 1, '2017-04-05 09:40:20', '2017-04-05 09:40:20', '[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nS. Sorgenfrei, C.-Y. Chiu, C. Nuckolls, and K.L. Shepard, <a href="/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Lissa_published_paper.pdf" target="_blank">"Charge sensing using point-functionalized carbon-nanotube transistors for single-molecule detection</a>," Proc. of IEEE/NIH Life Science Systems and Applications Workshop 2011 (LiSSA \'11).\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nWe have demonstrated that carbon-nanotube fieldeffect transistors act as highly sensitive single-molecule detectors when point functionalized. The hybridization kinetics of two complementary strands of DNA are associated with two-level fluctuations in the conductance of the nanotube to which the DNA is bound. We have studied the temperature dependence of the nanotube conductance and shown that the transport mechanism is consistent with Frenkel Poole emission, in which negatively charged DNA modulates a tunnel barrier at the point functionalized defect site. These transistors represent an important potential sensing platform for label-free single-molecule diagnostics.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]', 'Charge sensing using point-functionalized carbon-nanotube transistors for single-molecule detection', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '555-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-04-05 09:40:20', '2017-04-05 09:40:20', '', 555, 'http://bioee.dev/555-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(558, 1, '2011-01-04 18:22:04', '2011-01-04 18:22:04', '[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\' admin_preview_bg=\'\']\r\nS. Realov and K. L. Shepard, "<a href="/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/RealovShepardVLSI2011.pdf" target="_blank">On-Chip Combined C-V/I-V Transistor Characterization System in 45-nm CMOS</a>," Symposium on VLSI Circuits, 2011.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nAn on-chip transistor characterization system for combined C-V/I-V characterization is presented. Capacitance measurement uses a quasi-static charged-based measurement technique with atto-Farad resolution. Random and systematic variability in device I-V and C-V characteristics is studied. The random variability in intrinsic gate capacitance is shown to exhibit Pelgrom scaling. Correlation between I-V and C-V measurements is used to identify systematic channel-length variation gradients in a device array.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n[/av_toggle_container]', 'On-Chip Combined C-V/I-V Transistor Characterization System in 45-nm CMOS', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'on-chip-combined-c-vi-v-transistor-characterization-system-in-45-nm-cmos', '', '', '2017-04-05 10:28:00', '2017-04-05 10:28:00', '', 0, 'http://bioee.dev/?p=558', 0, 'post', '', 0) ;
