rials are described, including high frequency permeability measurements. The inductance of 2-turn coil inductors, for example, was enhanced up to about 6 times over the air core equivalent, with an inductance density of 130 nH/mm2 being achieved. The resistance of these non-laminated inductors was relatively large at high frequency due to magnetic and eddy current losses but is expected to improve as the yoke material/structure is further optimized, making electroplated yoke-containing inductors attractive for dc-dc power converters.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]', 'Integrated on-chip inductors with electroplated magnetic yokes', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '586-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-04-05 11:38:43', '2017-04-05 11:38:43', '', 586, 'http://bioee.dev/586-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(596, 1, '2017-04-05 11:39:13', '2017-04-05 11:39:13', '[av_one_full first min_height=\'\' vertical_alignment=\'\' space=\'\' custom_margin=\'\' margin=\'0px\' padding=\'0px\' border=\'\' border_color=\'\' radius=\'0px\' background_color=\'\' src=\'\' background_position=\'top left\' background_repeat=\'no-repeat\' animation=\'\' mobile_display=\'\']\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nJ. K. Rosenstein, M. Wanunu, C. A. Merchant, M. Drndic, and K. L. Shepard, "<a href="/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/nmeth.1932.pdf" target="_blank">Integrated nanopore sensing platform with sub-microsecond temporal resolution</a>," doi:10.1038/nmeth.1932, March 18, 2012.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full][av_toggle_container initial=\'0\' mode=\'accordion\' sort=\'\']\r\n[av_toggle title=\'Abstract\' tags=\'\']\r\nNanopore sensors have attracted considerable interest for high-throughput sensing of individual nucleic acids and proteins without the need for chemical labels or complex optics. A prevailing problem in nanopore applications is that the transport kinetics of single biomolecules are often faster than the measurement time resolution. Methods to slow down biomolecular transport can be troublesome and are at odds with the natural goal of high-throughput sensing. Here we introduce a low-noise measurement platform that integrates a complementary metal-oxide semiconductor (CMOS) preamplifier with solid-state nanopores in thin silicon nitride membranes. With this platform we achieved a signal-to-noise ratio exceeding five at a bandwidth of 1MHz, which to our knowledge is the highest bandwidth nanopore recording to date. We demonstrate transient signals as brief as 1s from short DNA molecules as well as current signatures during molecular passage events that shed light on submolecular DNA configurations in small nanopores.\r\n[/av_toggle]\r\n\r\n[/av_toggle_container]', 'Integrated nanopore sensing platform with sub-microsecond temporal resolution', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '583-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-04-05 11:39:13', '2017-04-05 11:39:13', '', 583, 'http://bioee.dev/583-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
