(1138, 1, '2014-02-01 17:21:40', '2014-02-01 17:21:40', 'In a <a href="http://www.nature.com/ncomms/2014/140210/ncomms4256/full/ncomms4256.html">study</a> published today in <a href="http://www.nature.com/ncomms/index.html">Nature Communications</a>, a research team led by <a href="http://www.bioee.ee.columbia.edu/~shepard/">Ken Shepard</a>, professor of electrical engineering and biomedical engineering at Columbia Engineering, and <a href="http://www.dietrichlab.com/">Lars Dietrich</a>, assistant professor of biological sciences at Columbia University, has demonstrated that integrated circuit technology, the basis of modern computers and communications devices, can be used for a most unusual applicationthe study of signaling in bacterial colonies. They have developed a chip based on complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor (CMOS) technology that enables them to electrochemically image the signaling molecules from these colonies spatially and temporally. In effect, they have developed chips that listen to bacteria.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://engineering.columbia.edu/chips-listen-bacteria-0" target="_blank">Learn More</a>', 'Dan Bellin\'s new paper in Nature Communications', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dan-bellins-new-paper-in-nature-communications', '', '', '2017-04-11 17:09:47', '2017-04-11 17:09:47', '', 0, 'http://bioee.dev/?p=1138', 0, 'post', '', 0),
